	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>EU uses traditional trade-policy tools to manage price volatility</h1>

			
			<h4>
												01 March 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>On 17 February 2011, the EC announced that ‘import duties on certain cereals imported into the EU will be suspended next week until the end of June 2011 in order to ease the pressure on the EU market’. The tariff suspension ‘relates to existing tariff rate quotas for low and medium quality soft wheat and for feed barley, where the preferential tariffs of 12 €/tonne and 16 €/tonne respectively will be reduced to zero for the volumes permitted under the quota’. (These volumes are 2,989,240 tonnes for low-quality soft wheat, with a country-specific quota of 572,000 tonnes for imports originating in the US and 38,853 tonnes for imports originating in Canada, with the remainder being open to third countries; and a feed barley TRQ of 306,215 tonnes). Import duties have been set at zero for durum wheat and high-quality soft wheat since the beginning of the 2010/11 marketing year, while the import duties for maize have been set at zero since 17 August 2010, and those for rye and sorghum have been set at zero since 19 October 2010.</p><p>This action was taken in response to appeals from EU feed groups and the livestock industry. Analysts suggest that the decision could prompt ‘significant’ shipments to certain regions of the EU, notably Spain. Press reports suggest that EU grain prices have been rising faster than world market prices, given the EU’s ‘relatively thin export surplus compared to the US’.</p><p>Meanwhile, analysts Stratégie Grains have for a second time ‘cut [their] forecast for the European Union grain harvest this year’, in the face of dry weather across a range of production areas. While EU production is still projected to grow 5.5% compared to last year, the expansion will not be as great as price levels might have suggested. With China and the US facing similar problems of ‘moisture shortages’, the EU decision to suspend tariffs could enable imports to take place before a resurgence of price increases, following poor projected harvests and reduced stock levels. The EC takes the view that encouraging the import of feed grains ‘can be done without damaging the global market’.</p>
		
		
