				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>While the EU has bound tariffs for all cereals in the WTO, applied tariffs are determined ‘on the basis of the differences between the effective EU intervention price for cereals, multiplied by 1.55 and a representative cif import price for cereals’. There is also a range of TRQ arrangements (i.e. a quota for import at a tariff much lower than the standards duty). Modifying duties under these TRQ arrangements, including setting them at zero, allows the EU to modify applied tariffs in response to market conditions. Significantly, these quotas exceed the level of total EU soft-wheat imports projected for 2010, and are only marginally less than total EU soft-wheat imports in 2009. The EU thus applies a relatively sophisticated tariff policy to ensure access to competitively priced grains for European livestock producers and food processors.</p><p>This policy approach potentially has important lessons for ACP cereals producers, since it highlights the extent to which the EU continues to make use of traditional trade-policy tools in managing access to EU agricultural markets in the light of wider EU agri-food sector policy objectives. This would appear to hold relevance in the context of the ongoing EPA negotiations, especially regarding the current debate on the use of traditional agricultural trade-policy tools by ACP governments.</p>
		</div>
		
